# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: kyushu
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:kyushu/abura-zōmen] The dish is made by mixing boiled sōmen noodles with a sauce containing oil, which prevents the noodles from sticking together, giving it a distinctive texture.
[src:kyushu/abura-zōmen] Although wheat was not traditionally cultivated and *sōmen* production was not local to the Amami region, there are several theories as to why sōmen became widely established there.
[src:kyushu/abura-zōmen] One theory suggests that *sōmen* was introduced from Satsuma during the Edo period, and because dried noodles could be preserved for long periods, they became a common food in Amami.
[src:kyushu/abura-zōmen] However, the exact origin remains uncertain.
[src:kyushu/abura-zōmen] Due to its simplicity, *abura-zōmen* is still widely prepared in ordinary households in the region today.
[src:kyushu/abura-zōmen] Many restaurants specializing in regional cuisine proudly serve *abura-zōmen*, reinforcing its deep cultural roots.
[src:kyushu/abura-zōmen] It has become a popular dish not only among locals but also among travelers from outside the prefecture.
[src:kyushu/abura-zōmen] During celebrations, rice planting and harvesting, and other occasions where large groups of people gathered, *abura-zōmen* was commonly prepared.
[src:kyushu/abura-zōmen] It is considered an essential dish, particularly during the *hachigwachi uduri* (Northern Amami-Oshima: 八月踊) festival held in the Amami Islands.
[src:kyushu/abura-zōmen] First, thinly sliced pork is stir-fried in oil.
[src:kyushu/abura-zōmen] Then, dried anchovies and boiled sōmen are added, and dashi broth is poured over the mixture.
[src:kyushu/abura-zōmen] Once the oil and dashi emulsify, garlic chives are added, and the flavor is adjusted with soy sauce and other seasonings.
[src:kyushu/abura-zōmen] It is ideal to leave a small amount of broth remaining in the dish.
[src:kyushu/abura-zōmen] The type and amount of dashi broth can vary depending on the region, household, or restaurant.
[src:kyushu/abura-zōmen] In some cases, chicken broth similar to that used in *keihan* is employed, while others use broth made from silver-stripe round herring (*kibinago*, キビナゴ).
[src:kyushu/abura-zōmen] Additionally, some versions are made with less broth for a drier finish, whereas others are served with more broth, resembling *nyūmen* (にゅうめん).
[src:kyushu/abura-zōmen] In terms of ingredients, besides garlic chives, various locally available vegetables may also be included.
[src:kyushu/aichi-prefecture] Nagoya is the capital and largest city of Aichi Prefecture, and the fourth-largest city in Japan.
[src:kyushu/aichi-prefecture] Other major cities include Toyota, Okazaki, and Ichinomiya.
[src:kyushu/aichi-prefecture] Aichi Prefecture and Nagoya form the core of the Chūkyō metropolitan area, the third-largest metropolitan area in Japan and one of the largest metropolitan areas in the world.
[src:kyushu/aichi-prefecture] Aichi Prefecture is located on Japan's Pacific Ocean coast and forms part of the Tōkai region, a subregion of the Chūbu region and Kansai region.
[src:kyushu/aichi-prefecture] Aichi Prefecture is home to the Toyota Motor Corporation.
[src:kyushu/aichi-prefecture] Aichi Prefecture had many locations with the Higashiyama Zoo and Botanical Gardens, The Chubu Centrair International Airport, and the Legoland Japan Resort.
[src:kyushu/aichi-prefecture] Located near the centre of the Japanese main island of Honshu, Aichi Prefecture faces the Ise and Mikawa Bays to the south and borders Shizuoka Prefecture to the east, Nagano Prefecture to the northeast, Gifu Prefecture to the north, and Mie Prefecture to the west.
[src:kyushu/aichi-prefecture] It measures 106 km (66 mi) east to west and 94 km (58 mi) south to north and forms a major portion of the Nōbi Plain.
[src:kyushu/aichi-prefecture] With an area of 5,172.48 square kilometres (1,997.11 sq mi) it accounts for approximately 1.36% of the total surface area of Japan.
[src:kyushu/aichi-prefecture] The highest spot is Chausuyama at 1,415 m (4,642 ft) above sea level.
[src:kyushu/aichi-prefecture] The western part of the prefecture is dominated by Nagoya, Japan's third largest city, and its suburbs, while the eastern part is less densely populated but still contains several major industrial centres.
[src:kyushu/aichi-prefecture] Due to its robust economy, for the period from October 2005 to October 2006, Aichi was the fastest growing prefecture in terms of population, beating Tokyo, at 7.4% and around with after Saitama Prefecture.
[src:kyushu/aichi-prefecture] As of 1 April 2012, 23% of the total land area of the prefecture was designated as Natural Parks, namely the Aichi Kōgen, Hida-Kisogawa, Mikawa Wan, and Tenryū-Okumikawa Quasi-National Parks along with seven Prefectural Natural Parks.
[src:kyushu/aichi-prefecture] Thirty-eight cities are located in Aichi Prefecture.
[src:kyushu/aichi-prefecture] As of 2001, Aichi Prefecture's population was 50.03% male and 49.97% female.
[src:kyushu/aichi-prefecture] 139,540 residents (nearly 2% of the population) are of foreign nationality.
[src:kyushu/aichi-prefecture] Originally, the region was divided into two provinces of Owari and Mikawa.
[src:kyushu/aichi-prefecture] After the Meiji Restoration, Owari and Mikawa were united into a single entity.
[src:kyushu/aichi-prefecture] In 1871, after the abolition of the han system, Owari, with the exception of the Chita Peninsula, was established as Nagoya Prefecture, while Mikawa combined with the Chita Peninsula and formed Nukata Prefecture.
[src:kyushu/aichi-prefecture] Nagoya Prefecture was renamed to Aichi Prefecture in April 1872 and was united with Nukata Prefecture on 27 November of the same year.
[src:kyushu/aichi-prefecture] The government of Aichi Prefecture is located in the Aichi Prefectural Government Office in Nagoya, which is the old capital of Owari.
[src:kyushu/aichi-prefecture] The Aichi Prefectural Police and its predecessor organisations have been responsible for law enforcement in the prefecture since 1871.
[src:kyushu/aichi-prefecture] The Expo 2005 World Exposition was held in Seto and Nagakute.
[src:kyushu/aichi-prefecture] In the third volume of the *Man'yōshū* there is a poem by Takechi Kurohito that reads: "The cry of the crane, calling to Sakurada; it sounds like the tide, draining from Ayuchi flats, hearing the crane cry".
[src:kyushu/aichi-prefecture] Ayuchi is the original form of the name *Aichi*, and the Fujimae tidal flat is all that remains of the earlier Ayuchi-gata.
[src:kyushu/aichi-prefecture] For a time, an Aichi Station existed on the Kansai Line (at the time the Kansai Railway) between Nagoya and Hatta stations, but its role was overtaken by Sasashima-raibu Station on the Aonami Line and Komeno Station on the Kintetsu Nagoya Line.
[src:kyushu/aichi-prefecture] Gross domestic product (2018) is the second largest in Japan, the shipment value of manufactured goods (2018) is the first in Japan, annual product sales (2019) is the third largest in Japan, and its agricultural output (2018) is eighth in Japan.
[src:kyushu/aichi-prefecture] Aichi's agriculture industry and commerce are all ranked high in Japan, and the industrial structure is well-balanced.
[src:kyushu/aichi-prefecture] Companies headquartered in Aichi include the following.
[src:kyushu/aichi-prefecture] Companies such as Fuji Heavy Industries, Mitsubishi Motors, Pfizer, Sony, Suzuki, Bodycote, and Volkswagen Group also operate plants or branch offices in Aichi.
[src:kyushu/aichi-prefecture] The sports teams listed below are based in Aichi.
[src:kyushu/aichi-prefecture] Notable sites in Aichi include the Meiji Mura open-air architectural museum in Inuyama, which preserves historic buildings from Japan's Meiji and Taishō periods, including the reconstructed lobby of Frank Lloyd Wright's old Imperial Hotel (which originally stood in Tokyo from 1923 to 1967).
[src:kyushu/aichi-prefecture] Other popular sites in Aichi include the tour of Toyota car factory in the city by the same name, the monkey park in Inuyama, and the castles in Nagoya, Okazaki, Toyohashi, and Inuyama.
[src:kyushu/aichi-prefecture] Aichi Prefecture has many wonderful beaches.
[src:kyushu/aichi-prefecture] For example, Himakajima Beach, Shinojima Beach, Akabane Beach and Utsumi Beach.
[src:kyushu/akita-prefecture] Akita is the capital and largest city of Akita Prefecture.
[src:kyushu/akita-prefecture] Other major cities include Yokote, Daisen, and Yurihonjō.
[src:kyushu/akita-prefecture] Akita Prefecture is located on the coast of the Sea of Japan and extends east to the Ōu Mountains, the longest mountain range in Japan, at the border with Iwate Prefecture.
[src:kyushu/akita-prefecture] Akita Prefecture formed the northern half of the historic Dewa Province with Yamagata Prefecture.
[src:kyushu/akita-prefecture] The region of Akita was created from the ancient provinces of Dewa and Mutsu.
[src:kyushu/akita-prefecture] Separated from the principal Japanese centres of commerce, politics, and population by several hundred kilometres and by the Ōu and Dewa mountain ranges to the east, Akita remained largely isolated from Japanese society until after the year 600.
[src:kyushu/akita-prefecture] Akita was a region of hunter-gatherers and principally nomadic tribes.
[src:kyushu/akita-prefecture] The first historical record of what is now Akita Prefecture dates to 658, when Abe no Hirafu conquered the native Ezo tribes at what are now the cities of Akita and Noshiro.
[src:kyushu/akita-prefecture] Abe, then governor of Koshi Province (the northwestern part of Honshū bordering the Sea of Japan), established a fort on the Mogami River, and thus began the Japanese settlement of the region.
[src:kyushu/akita-prefecture] In 733, a new military settlement (later renamed Akita Castle) was built in what is now the Takashimizu area of Akita, and more permanent roads and structures were developed.
[src:kyushu/akita-prefecture] The region was used as a base of operations for the Japanese empire as it drove the native Ezo people from northern Honshū.
[src:kyushu/akita-prefecture] Governance of the region shifted hands several times.
[src:kyushu/akita-prefecture] During the Tokugawa shogunate it was appropriated to the Satake clan, who ruled the region for 260 years and developed the agriculture and mining industries that are still predominant today.
[src:kyushu/akita-prefecture] Throughout this period, it was classified as part of Dewa Province.
[src:kyushu/akita-prefecture] In 1871, during the Meiji Restoration, Dewa Province was reshaped and the old daimyō domains were abolished and administratively reconstructed, resulting in the modern-day borders of Akita.
[src:kyushu/akita-prefecture] The famous Heian period waka poet, Ono no Komachi, is said to have been born in Yuzawa City, Ogachi Town, located in the southeast of the prefecture.
[src:kyushu/akita-prefecture] Located on the north-western side of Honshu, Akita Prefecture is adjacent to the Sea of Japan to the west and borders four other prefectures: Aomori in the north, Iwate in the east, Miyagi in the southeast, and Yamagata in the south.
[src:kyushu/akita-prefecture] The borders of Akita Prefecture roughly form a rectangle that is 169 kilometres (105 miles) from north to south and 86 kilometres (54 miles) from west to east.
[src:kyushu/akita-prefecture] The Oga Peninsula is a prominent feature of the western edge, while the Ōu Mountains mark the eastern border and the higher Dewa Mountains run parallel through the center.
[src:kyushu/akita-prefecture] Like much of northern Japan, the prefecture has cold winters, particularly in areas farther from the sea.
[src:kyushu/akita-prefecture] Like much of the Tōhoku Region, Akita's economy remains dominated by traditional industries such as agriculture, fishing, and forestry.
[src:kyushu/akita-prefecture] This has led many young people to migrate to Tokyo and other large cities.
[src:kyushu/akita-prefecture] Akita Prefecture has seen some of the most severe population decline in Japan: it is one of four prefectures in Japan registering declines in population since 1955.
[src:kyushu/akita-prefecture] Its population also has the lowest percentage of children (defined as under the age of 15), at 9.3% in 2022, down from 11.2% in 2010.
[src:kyushu/akita-prefecture] 38.6% of residents are 65 or older, the highest percentage of any Japanese prefecture.
[src:kyushu/akita-prefecture] As of October 1, 2022, it has an estimated population of 944,902 people.
[src:kyushu/akita-prefecture] The high rate of depopulation in Akita Prefecture has led smaller communities to merge with each other, which has affected the smallest of these merged communities.
[src:kyushu/akita-prefecture] As depopulation in these communities continues, educational and health facilities have closed in some areas, encouraging families to migrate to larger cities for better access to health and educational opportunities and perpetuating the decline in population.
[src:kyushu/akita-prefecture] This decline, combined with an aging population, has been concerning for rural communities.
[src:kyushu/akita-prefecture] Akita, 秋田, meaning autumn rice paddy, is famous for rice farming and its sake breweries.
[src:kyushu/akita-prefecture] It is well known for having the highest consumption of sake in Japan and is thought to be the origin of the Akita breed of dog which carries the prefecture's name.
[src:kyushu/akita-prefecture] The women of the region, referred to as *Akita Bijin* (秋田美人, *'Beauties of Akita'*), have also gained widespread renown for their white skin, rounded faces and high voices, all of which are considered highly desirable.
[src:kyushu/akita-prefecture] Ono no Komachi is a famous example of an *Akita bijin*.
[src:kyushu/akita-prefecture] Recently there have been efforts to revitalize rural communities facing depopulation with different forms of green tourism and agritourism.
[src:kyushu/akita-prefecture] These efforts are primarily aimed at attracting urbanites and foreign tourists to Akita Prefecture, advertising its pristine forests, sprawling rice fields, and range of cultures.
[src:kyushu/akita-prefecture] There has been a push for home stays, farmers markets for locally produced foods, and the integration of outsiders into local cultural practices.
[src:kyushu/akita-prefecture] The Namahage ritual in Oga on New Year's Eve draws a large number of tourists to Akita Prefecture every year.
[src:kyushu/akita-prefecture] Near Lake Tazawa, there are a number of hot springs resorts (*onsen*).
[src:kyushu/akita-prefecture] These are popular with tourists from all over Japan.
[src:kyushu/akita-prefecture] In addition, numerous seasonal festivals (*matsuri*) offer a glimpse of rural or traditional Japan.
[src:kyushu/akita-prefecture] Some famous examples are the Akita Kantō, the Omagari Fireworks, Namahage Festival, and the Yokote Kamakura Festivals.
[src:kyushu/akita-prefecture] Kakunodate, known as the little Kyoto, features many preserved samurai houses.
[src:kyushu/akita-prefecture] The Aoyagi house is the former residence of Odano Naotake, who illustrated Japan's first modern guide to human anatomy.
[src:kyushu/akita-prefecture] The house is now a museum and gallery of medical illustrations and traditional crafts.
[src:kyushu/akita-prefecture] Starting in 2009, Akita began experiencing a huge surge in Korean tourism after the airing of the popular drama *Iris*, which featured several scenes shot in Akita, most notably at Lake Tazawa and Oga's GAO Aquarium.
[src:kyushu/akumaki] Akumaki is made by soaking glutinous rice wrapped in bamboo leaves in lye overnight.
[src:kyushu/akumaki] Because it's slightly bitter, it's typically eaten with blended sugar and toasted soybean flour *(kinako)*, with a little salt or soaked in honey.
[src:kyushu/akumaki] It has an unusual flavor and is considered an acquired taste.
[src:kyushu/akumaki] It is said that akumaki began as a long-term provision for samurai during the Battle of Sekigahara (1600) or the Japanese invasions of Korea (1592–1598).
[src:kyushu/akumaki] Also, Saigō Takamori (1821–1877) took akumaki as a nonperishable commodity to the battlefield during the Satsuma Rebellion (1877).
[src:kyushu/akumaki] Akumaki became popular in the north of Miyazaki Prefecture and Kumamoto Prefecture due to that rebellion.
[src:kyushu/akumaki] It can be kept for about one week at normal temperature, for about two weeks in a refrigerator, and can also be frozen.
[src:kyushu/akumaki] Vacuum-packed akumaki can be found in many places as a souvenir, but it is usually a homemade confection.
[src:kyushu/akumaki] Recently, since the opening of the Kyushu Shinkansen train line, akumaki has attracted considerable attention as a slow food.
[src:kyushu/akumaki] Akumaki is sold in hotels of Kagoshima, roadside stations *(michi no eki)*, over the internet and in supermarkets throughout Kagoshima prefecture.
[src:kyushu/alexander-island] Alexander Island was discovered on January 28, 1821, by a Russian expedition under Fabian Gottlieb von Bellingshausen, who named it Alexander I Land for the reigning Tsar Alexander I of Russia.
[src:kyushu/alexander-island] What, in fact, is an island, was believed to be part of the Antarctic mainland until 1940.
[src:kyushu/alexander-island] Its insular nature was proven in December 1940, by a two-person sledge party composed of Finn Ronne and Carl Eklund of the United States Antarctic Service.
[src:kyushu/alexander-island] In the 1950s, a British base administered as part of the British Antarctic Territory was constructed as Fossil Bluff (*Base KG*).
[src:kyushu/alexander-island] The island was claimed by the United Kingdom in 1908 as part of the British Antarctic Territory.
[src:kyushu/alexander-island] Territorial claims have also been set by both Chile (in 1940) and Argentina (in 1942).
[src:kyushu/alexander-island] Currently, under the Antarctic Treaty no claim has been officially recognized.
[src:kyushu/alexander-island] The island contains the British Fossil Bluff meteorological centre and refuelling base.
[src:kyushu/alexander-island] The surface of Alexander Island is predominantly ice-covered.
[src:kyushu/alexander-island] There exist some exposed nunataks and a few ice-free areas of significant size, including Ablation Point Massif.
[src:kyushu/alexander-island] The nunataks are the peaks of north–south trending mountain ranges and hills.
[src:kyushu/alexander-island] They include the Colbert, Havre, Lassus, Rouen, Sofia University, and Walton Mountains, the Staccato Peaks, the Lully Foothills, the Finlandia Foothills, the Elgar Uplands, and the Douglas Range.
[src:kyushu/alexander-island] These mountains, peaks, hills, and uplands are surrounded by a permanent ice sheet, which consists of glaciers that flow off of Alexander Island.
[src:kyushu/alexander-island] These glaciers flow west into the Bach and Wilkins Ice Shelves and Bellingshausen Sea, and east into the George VI Ice Shelf.
[src:kyushu/alexander-island] The George VI Ice Shelf is fed by both by outlet glaciers from the ice cap on Palmer Land and Alexander Island.
[src:kyushu/alexander-island] Another notable feature of Alexander Island is Hodgson Lake, a former subglacial lake that has emerged from under an ice sheet that had covered it.
[src:kyushu/alexander-island] Hodgson Lake is 2 km (1.2 mi) long by 1.5 km (0.93 mi), and has a 93.4 m (306 ft) deep water column that lies sealed beneath a 3.6 to 4.0 m (11.8 to 13.1 ft) thick perennial lake ice.
[src:kyushu/alexander-island] The northern side of Hodgson Lake is bounded by the Saturn Glacier, which flows east into George VI Sound, while the southern side of Hodgson Lake is bounded by the northern face of Citadel Bastion.
[src:kyushu/alexander-island] During the Last Glacial Maximum, Hodgson Lake was covered by the ice sheet at least 470 m (1,540 ft) thick.
[src:kyushu/alexander-island] This ice sheet started thinning about 13,500 years ago.
[src:kyushu/alexander-island] It retreated and left Hodgson Lake covered by perennial ice sometime before 11,000 years ago.
[src:kyushu/alexander-island] This lake has been covered by perennial ice since that time.
[src:kyushu/alexander-island] Other features on the island include Damocles Point and Mount Tyrrell.
[src:kyushu/alexander-island] The LeMay Group consists of variably-deformed and metamorphosed sedimentary and igneous rocks.
[src:kyushu/alexander-island] Although it is dominated by deformed arkosic sedimentary rocks, it includes turbiditic greywackes, black mudstones, and conglomerates.
[src:kyushu/alexander-island] The 4-kilometre (2.5-mile) thick Upper Jurassic to Lower Cretaceous Fossil Bluff Group sedimentary rocks outcrop as a 250 km (160 mi) long by 30 km (19 mi) wide belt along the eastern coast.
[src:kyushu/alexander-island] This Fossil Bluff Group consists of a basal deep-marine assemblage 2,200 meters (7,200 feet) thick, overlain by a mudstone assemblage up to 950 m (3,120 ft) thick, followed by a shallow-marine assemblage of coarsening upward sandstones.
[src:kyushu/alexander-island] Alkali basalts erupted after the cessation of subduction.
[src:kyushu/alexander-island] These range in age from the tephrites at Mount Pinafore (5.5–7.6 Ma), to the basanites at Rothschild Island (5.5 Ma) and Hornpipe Heights (2.5 Ma), to the alkali and olivine basalts on Beethoven Peninsula (<1–2.5 Ma).
[src:kyushu/alexander-island] The LeMay Range Fault trends N-S, parallel to the George VI Sound, and the Fossil Bluff Formation is downfaulted to the east of this fault against the LeMay Group.
[src:kyushu/alexander-island] Sand dykes are found against this fault zone and in many other parts of the Fossil Bay Formation.
[src:kyushu/alexander-island] Fossils within the Fossil Bluff Formation include ammonites, belemnites, bivalves, and serpulids.
[src:kyushu/amagi-railway-amagi-line] The **Amagi Line** (甘木線, *Amagi-sen*) is a Japanese railway line connecting Kiyama Station (on the Kagoshima Main Line), Kiyama and Amagi Station, Asakura.
[src:kyushu/amagi-railway-amagi-line] This is the only railway operated by the third-sector railway company **Amagi Railway** (甘木鉄道, *Amagi Tetsudō*).
[src:kyushu/amagi-railway-amagi-line] The company, and sometimes the line, are also called **Amatetsu** (甘鉄).
[src:kyushu/amagi-railway-amagi-line] The line was opened on April 28, 1939 by the Japanese National Railways (JNR) as the Amagi Line, in order to supply military equipment to Tachiarai Airfield.
[src:kyushu/amagi-railway-amagi-line] In 1981, the line was named a specified local line and considered for closure.
[src:kyushu/amagi-railway-amagi-line] On April 5, 1985, it was agreed that the line would be transferred to a newly created third sector railway company.
[src:kyushu/amagi-railway-amagi-line] Amagi Railway was thus created and inherited the former JNR line on April 1, 1986.
[src:kyushu/amagi-railway-amagi-line] While the conversion of the line into a bus route was unopposed by both Saga and Fukuoka Prefectures due to the Nishitetsu Amagi Line's existence, the municipalities Amagi and Miwa requested the line be kept in operation.
[src:kyushu/amagi-railway-amagi-line] After the transferring of the line, Ogōri Station was relocated by 400 meters to allow easier connection to the Nishitetsu Ogōri Station.
[src:kyushu/amagi-railway-amagi-line] The number of services were increased from seven return trips a day in 1982 to 42 in 2023 on weekdays.
[src:kyushu/amagi-railway-amagi-line] The AR400 series in use on the line is planned to be replaced by the ARe500 series starting from 2025.
[src:kyushu/amami-ōshima-island-tokunoshima-island-northern-part-of-okinawa-island-and-iriom] UNESCO voted to list it as a World Heritage Site in 2021.
[src:kyushu/amami-ōshima-island-tokunoshima-island-northern-part-of-okinawa-island-and-iriom] In the long history of the campaign for registration, this candidate site was renamed at least twice.
[src:kyushu/amami-ōshima-island-tokunoshima-island-northern-part-of-okinawa-island-and-iriom] When a panel of natural scientists formally added it to Japan's tentative list of nomination, it was given the name of *Ryūkyū Shotō*.
[src:kyushu/amami-ōshima-island-tokunoshima-island-northern-part-of-okinawa-island-and-iriom] This followed a convention of natural sciences but is inconsistent with the official definition provided by the Japanese government, which excludes the Amami Islands from the *Ryūkyū Shotō*.
[src:kyushu/amami-ōshima-island-tokunoshima-island-northern-part-of-okinawa-island-and-iriom] Moreover, the Amami Islands and Kagoshima Prefecture as a whole voiced a strong opposition to having the label *Ryūkyū* imposed on themselves.
[src:kyushu/amami-ōshima-island-tokunoshima-island-northern-part-of-okinawa-island-and-iriom] As a result, the candidate site was renamed to *Amami–Ryukyu*.
[src:kyushu/amami-ōshima-island-tokunoshima-island-northern-part-of-okinawa-island-and-iriom] In late 2015, UNESCO's committee recommended Japan "from a technical perspective" to use an accurate designation of the areas under nomination.
[src:kyushu/amami-ōshima-island-tokunoshima-island-northern-part-of-okinawa-island-and-iriom] In response, the candidate site was renamed again to the current, highly descriptive name in 2016.
[src:kyushu/amami-ōshima-island-tokunoshima-island-northern-part-of-okinawa-island-and-iriom] Within the total area of 426.98 square kilometres (164.86 sq mi) are found some 1,819 vascular plants, 21 terrestrial mammals, 394 birds, 21 amphibians, 36 terrestrial reptiles, and 267 inland fish, including endemics such as the Amami rabbit, Okinawa rail, and Iriomote cat.
[src:kyushu/amami-ōshima-island-tokunoshima-island-northern-part-of-okinawa-island-and-iriom] Of the above, 189 species of vascular plant are endemic (c.10% of the total number of species found), as are 13 terrestrial mammals (62%), 5 birds, 18 amphibians (86%), 23 reptiles (64%), and 14 inland fish.
[src:kyushu/amami-ōshima-island-tokunoshima-island-northern-part-of-okinawa-island-and-iriom] Of the 6,153 insect species found, 1,607 are endemic.
[src:kyushu/kyushu] There is a theory that Kyushu was in ancient times home to its own independent dynasty, where a unique, southern-influenced culture and tradition distinct from that of Honshu flourished.
[src:kyushu/kyushu] In the 8th-century Taihō Code reforms, Dazaifu was established as a special administrative term for the region.
[src:kyushu/kyushu] The island is mountainous, and Japan's largest active volcano, Mount Aso at 1,591 metres (5,220 ft), is on Kyushu.
[src:kyushu/kyushu] There are many other signs of tectonic activity, including numerous areas of hot springs.
[src:kyushu/kyushu] The most famous of these are in Beppu, on the east shore, and around Mt.
[src:kyushu/kyushu] The island is separated from Honshu by the Kanmon Straits.
[src:kyushu/kyushu] Being the nearest island to the Asian continent, historically it is the gateway to Japan.
[src:kyushu/kyushu] The total area is 36,782.37 km2 (14,201.75 sq mi) which makes it the 37th largest island in the world.
[src:kyushu/kyushu] It is slightly larger than Taiwan's total area of 35,808 km2 (13,826 sq mi).
[src:kyushu/kyushu] The highest elevation is 1791 meters (5876 feet) on Mount Kujū.
[src:kyushu/kyushu] The name *Kyūshū* comes from the nine ancient provinces of Saikaidō situated on the island: Chikuzen, Chikugo, Hizen, Higo, Buzen, Bungo, Hyūga, Ōsumi, and Satsuma.
[src:kyushu/kyushu] Kyushu has 10.1 percent of the population of Japan.
[src:kyushu/kyushu] Most of Kyushu's population is concentrated along the northwest, in the cities of Fukuoka and Kitakyushu, with population corridors stretching southwest into Sasebo and Nagasaki and south into Kumamoto and Kagoshima.
[src:kyushu/kyushu] Except for Oita and Miyazaki, the eastern seaboard is sparsely populated.
[src:kyushu/kyushu] Politically, Kyushu is described as a stronghold of the Liberal Democratic Party.
[src:kyushu/kyushu] Per Japanese census data, the Kyushu region's population with Ryukyu Islands (Okinawa and Kagoshima Prefectures) has experienced a large decline since around 2000.
[src:kyushu/kyushu] However, the population decline in total is mild because of the relatively high birth rate of Ryukyuans both within the Ryukyuan lands (Okinawa and Kagoshima) and throughout the Kyushu region.
[src:kyushu/kyushu] In addition, the other prefectures in Kyushu also have exceptionally high TFRs compared to the rest of Japan.
[src:kyushu/kyushu] Parts of Kyushu have a subtropical climate, particularly Miyazaki Prefecture and Kagoshima Prefecture.
[src:kyushu/kyushu] Major agricultural products are rice, tea, tobacco, sweet potatoes, and soy.
[src:kyushu/kyushu] Besides the volcanic area of the south, there are significant mud hot springs in the northern part of the island, around Beppu.
[src:kyushu/kyushu] The springs are the site of occurrence of certain extremophile microorganisms, which are capable of surviving in extremely hot environments.
[src:kyushu/kyushu] There are two World Natural Heritage sites in Kyushu: Yakushima (registered in 1993) and Amami-Ōshima Island, Tokunoshima Island, northern part of Okinawa Island, and Iriomote Island (registered in 2021).
[src:kyushu/kyushu] Kyushu's economy accounts for approximately 10% of Japan's total economic output, making it comparable to countries such as Iran, Norway, Austria, the United Arab Emirates, and Thailand.
[src:kyushu/kyushu] It is the fourth largest economic region in Japan, following the three major metropolitan areas of Tokyo, Osaka, and Nagoya.
[src:kyushu/kyushu] Kyushu's economy has a well-balanced industrial structure, ranging from primary industries such as agriculture, to secondary industries such as manufacturing, and tertiary industries such as retail, services, and tourism.
[src:kyushu/kyushu] Agricultural output in the region amounts to 1.8 trillion yen (20% share of the national total), and the region is a major domestic production center for the automobile and semiconductor industries.
[src:kyushu/kyushu] Kyushu also has a thriving healthcare industry, including medical and nursing care, and numerous research and manufacturing facilities in the fields of hydrogen, solar power, and other renewable energies.
[src:kyushu/kyushu] Kyushu is a region with strong economic ties to Asia.
[src:kyushu/kyushu] For example, Asia accounted for 420 (77.9%) of the 539 overseas expansion cases of Kyushu-Yamaguchi companies from 2010 to 2019, and Asia accounted for 61.1% of Kyushu-Yamaguchi's total exports in 2019, 7.4 percentage points higher than the nation as a whole.
[src:kyushu/kyushu] As the logistics node between Japan and Asia, the ports of Hakata and Kitakyushu handle a large number of international containers.
[src:kyushu/kyushu] In addition, the number of cruise ship calls in 2019 was 772, with Kyushu accounting for 26.9% of the nation's total.
[src:kyushu/kyushu] Kyushu is noted for various types of porcelain, including Arita, Imari, Satsuma, and Karatsu.
[src:kyushu/kyushu] Heavy industry is concentrated in the north around Fukuoka, Kitakyushu, Nagasaki, and Oita and includes chemicals, automobiles, semiconductors, metal processing, shipbuilding, etc.
[src:kyushu/kyushu] The island of Tanegashima hosts the Tanegashima Space Center, which is the largest rocket-launch complex in Japan.
[src:kyushu/kyushu] Kyushu is linked to the larger island of Honshu by the Kanmon Railway Tunnel, which carries the non-Shinkansen trains of the Kyushu Railway Company, and the newer Shin-Kanmon Tunnel carrying the San'yō Shinkansen.
[src:kyushu/kyushu] Railways on the island are operated by the Kyushu Railway Company and West Japan Railway Company, as well as a variety of smaller companies such as Amagi Railway and Nishitetsu Railway.
[src:kyushu/kyushu] Kyushu Shinkansen trains operate between major cities on the island, such as Fukuoka and Kagoshima, with an additional route between Takeo-Onsen and Nagasaki which has been in operation since September 2022.
[src:kyushu/kyushu] Kyushu is also known for its scenic train services, such as the Limited Express Yufuin no Mori and Limited Express Kawasemi Yamasemi.
[src:kyushu/kyushu] The Kanmon Bridge and Kanmon Roadway Tunnel also connect the island with Honshu, allowing for vehicular transport between the two.
[src:kyushu/kyushu] The Kyushu Expressway spans the length of the island, linking the Higashikyushu Expressway and Ibusuki Skyline, connecting major cities such as Fukuoka and Kumamoto along the way.
[src:kyushu/kyushu] There are also many quiet country roads, including popular tourist routes such as the Nichinan coast road and the Aso Panorama Line in Kumamoto Prefecture.
[src:kyushu/kyushu] Bus services are available and cover 2,400 routes within Kyushu's cities, connecting many other destinations.
[src:kyushu/kyushu] Several passenger and car ferry services connect both northern and southern Kyushu with main port cities on the main island of Honshu (Kobe, Osaka, Tokyo) and Shikoku.
[src:kyushu/kyushu] The island's main larger airport is served by Fukuoka Airport which provides most domestic and internationals flights.
[src:kyushu/kyushu] There are also smaller airports across island including Kumamoto Airport, Miyazaki Airport, Oita Airport, Saga Airport, Nagasaki Airport Kitakyushu Airport and Kagoshima Airport.
[src:kyushu/kyushu] Kyushu has maintained the strongest economic and cultural ties with Okinawa (Ryukyu) from ancient times to the present.
[src:kyushu/kyushu] Traces of Okinawan culture can be seen throughout Kyushu, and vice versa.
[src:kyushu/kyushu] Okinawan musical scales are often found in local folk songs, and there are many similarities in cuisine and language.
[src:kyushu/kyushu] Kyushu has a traditional instrument called the *gottan*, which resembles the *sanshin* and *shamisen*.
[src:kyushu/kyushu] Crafts of the reason include Hakata-ori (博多織), Beppu bamboo crafts(別府竹細工), Kurume Kasuri (久留米絣), and Sathuma Kiriko.
[src:kyushu/kyushu] People in Kyushu are known for being conservative even within Japan.
[src:kyushu/kyushu] In particular, men from Kyushu are often referred to as "Kyushu danji" (九州男児), evoking an image of being wild and strong.
[src:kyushu/kyushu] It is said that this term has existed since ancient times, originally used to inspire and encourage soldiers.
[src:kyushu/kyushu] Being from Kyushu is a source of great pride for its people.
[src:kyushu/kyushu] Thanks to this cultural spirit, Kyushu has preserved a rich variety of unique traditional cultures that continue to thrive today.
[src:kyushu/kyushu] The main features of Kyushu cuisine are the use of fresh ingredients and seasonings such as sweet soy sauce (Kyushu soy sauce) and barley miso, which differ from those used in Honshu.
[src:kyushu/kyushu] Each region has its own culinary characteristics: seafood-based dishes are prominent in the north, while meat dishes are more common in the south.
[src:kyushu/kyushu] Confectionery in Kyushu tends to use more sugar compared to other regions of Japan.
[src:kyushu/kyushu] This is because Kyushu has historically had close ties with Okinawa (Ryukyu), a major producer of sugar.
[src:kyushu/kyushu] As a result, many traditional sweets from Kyushu incorporate characteristics of Ryukyuan culture.
[src:kyushu/kyushu] In Kyushu, there exists a traditional stringed instrument known as the *gottan (ゴッタン)*, which developed independently within the region's unique cultural and geographic context.
[src:kyushu/kyushu] The instrument is considered to be a midpoint between the *shamisen* of mainland Japan and the *sanshin* of Okinawa, incorporating characteristics of both.
[src:kyushu/kyushu] Structurally, it resembles the sanshin more closely—for example, it lacks the *sawari*, a buzzing mechanism found in the shamisen.
[src:kyushu/kyushu] This absence, along with its simplified wooden box construction and single string, aligns it with the more minimalistic design typical of southern instruments.
[src:kyushu/kyushu] Musically, the *gottan* is sometimes used to perform melodies that reflect the Ryukyuan pentatonic scale, suggesting a subtle but notable influence from Okinawan musical traditions.
[src:kyushu/kyushu] While it remains a distinct and localized folk instrument of Kyushu, its sound and structure reveal traces of a broader cultural exchange within the southern Japanese archipelago, embodying a hybrid identity between the mainland and the Ryukyus.
[src:kyushu/kyushu] Historically some Kyushu-based sports team has competed in the top Japanese division of baseball (NPB), football (soccer) (J.League), basketball (B.League) or even rugby union (League One).
